<paper id="1865797552"><title>An Improved Data Stream Summary: The Count-Min Sketch and Its Applications</title><year>2004</year><authors><author org="Rutgers University" id="2190072679">Graham Cormode</author><author org="Rutgers University" id="2921339358">S. Muthukrishnan</author></authors><n_citation>129</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1493892051</reference><reference>1564015926</reference><reference>1584212476</reference><reference>1766932551</reference><reference>1785933978</reference><reference>1965972569</reference><reference>1977141583</reference><reference>1998783890</reference><reference>2001474264</reference><reference>2003262311</reference><reference>2013092187</reference><reference>2028660080</reference><reference>2039100193</reference><reference>2047424291</reference><reference>2053075747</reference><reference>2069980026</reference><reference>2080745194</reference><reference>2106163100</reference><reference>2112400233</reference><reference>2112452856</reference><reference>2122929038</reference><reference>2130297445</reference><reference>2141441292</reference><reference>2148706674</reference><reference>2156943642</reference><reference>2160681854</reference><reference>2167973519</reference><reference>2295205026</reference></references><venue id="1133508372" type="C">Latin American Symposium on Theoretical Informatics</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-24698-5_7</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.4307">Sublinear function</keyword><keyword weight="0.5167">Automatic summarization</keyword><keyword weight="0.5103">Data structure</keyword><keyword weight="0.57278">Data stream mining</keyword><keyword weight="0.43538">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.50499">Data stream</keyword><keyword weight="0.46992">Computational geometry</keyword><keyword weight="0.44015">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.61053">Count–min sketch</keyword><keyword weight="0.55052">Sketch</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We introduce a new sublinear space data structure—the Count-Min Sketch— for summarizing data streams. Our sketch allows fundamental queries in data stream summarization such as point, range, and inner product queries to be approximately answered very quickly; in addition, it can be applied to solve several important problems in data streams such as finding quantiles, frequent items, etc. The time and space bounds we show for using the CM sketch to solve these problems significantly improve those previously known — typically from 1/e 2 to 1/e in factor.</abstract></paper>